<script>

const S=[
  {num:"01",tag:"Commercial Courage",name:"Think Like a Business Owner",qs:[
    {q:"When I recommend a learning solution, I think about it in terms of…",o:["Getting the session planned and delivered on time.","Making sure the content is relevant and that delegates enjoy it.","How it connects to what the business is trying to achieve right now.","The specific behaviour change it needs to produce and how I will measure that against a business outcome."]},
    {q:"When I sit in a meeting with senior leaders, I feel…",o:["Slightly out of my depth — their world feels separate from mine.","Comfortable enough, but I mostly listen rather than lead the conversation.","Confident contributing, especially when the conversation touches on people and capability.","Genuinely at home — I speak the language of the business and they treat me as a peer."]},
    {q:"When I think about how I measure success in my role, I would say…",o:["I track completions, attendance and how well the session was rated.","I track some outcomes but I know the data I collect doesn't fully prove impact.","I measure behaviour change as well as reaction, and I can connect some of my work to business results.","Everything I do has a clear success measure tied to a business outcome. I report on impact, not activity."]},
    {q:"When a business challenge lands on my desk, my first instinct is to…",o:["Think about what training programme would address it.","Ask some questions before recommending — but training is usually where I land.","Diagnose the root cause first. Training might be the answer, but it might not.","Challenge the framing of the problem before I even think about a solution."]},
    {q:"When I think about how I influence decision-makers in my organisation, I would say…",o:["I don't really see influencing as part of my role — I respond to what I'm asked.","I try to influence but I'm not sure my voice lands at the level it needs to.","I build relationships with key stakeholders and use data and stories to make my case.","I am a credible influence on strategic decisions. Leaders seek my input before committing to direction."]},
    {q:"When I consider my current role and how it is positioned in the organisation, I would say…",o:["L&D or HR is seen as an administrative or compliance function where I work.","We are respected but mostly reactive — brought in to solve problems rather than prevent them.","We have a seat at the table for some strategic conversations and I am working to deepen that.","L&D or HR is seen as a genuine strategic partner. I am involved in decisions from the outset."]}
  ]},
  {num:"02",tag:"Relational Courage",name:"Challenge, Stretch and Hold Space",qs:[
    {q:"When a stakeholder asks me to design and deliver a programme I have reservations about, I…",o:["Deliver what is asked. It is not my place to question the brief.","Note my concerns privately but usually go ahead without raising them.","Ask gentle questions and try to nudge the brief in a better direction.","Have a direct and honest conversation about my concerns, with evidence, before agreeing to anything."]},
    {q:"When I am facilitating and the room gets uncomfortable — silence, conflict, an emotional moment — I…",o:["Move things on quickly. Discomfort feels unsafe and I want to protect the group.","Acknowledge it briefly and steer toward safer ground.","Hold the space for a while and trust the group, though I sometimes step in too soon.","Welcome it. I know discomfort is where the most significant learning happens and I am skilled enough to work with it."]},
    {q:"When I think about the professional conversations I avoid, I would say…",o:["There are several I consistently avoid — with leaders, stakeholders or colleagues.","There are one or two I have been putting off. I know I need to have them.","I have most of the conversations I need to, though I sometimes soften them more than I should.","I have the conversations that need to be had. I have learned to be honest with care rather than kind at the expense of truth."]},
    {q:"When I think about stretching learners beyond their comfort zone, I feel…",o:["Nervous. I worry about negative feedback or people feeling unsafe.","I stretch people sometimes, but I pull back when I sense resistance.","Comfortable creating stretch, and I am getting better at holding it without rescuing people.","This is one of my strengths. I know how to take people to the edge of their comfort and work with them there."]},
    {q:"When I think about how I influence the people I work with — colleagues, leaders, learners — I would say…",o:["I don't think about influencing. I focus on delivering well.","I rely mainly on my expertise to persuade people. If the content is good, it speaks for itself.","I adapt how I communicate to different audiences and I am building my ability to influence without authority.","Influencing is central to how I work. I shape thinking, shift perspectives and create movement in people — that is my craft."]},
    {q:"When a colleague or leader pushes back on something I believe is right, my usual response is to…",o:["Back down. It's not worth the conflict and I'm probably missing something.","Hold my position briefly, then find a compromise that keeps everyone comfortable.","Make my case clearly and listen to their view — I'll adapt if they persuade me, but I won't just fold.","Hold the tension. I can sit with disagreement, hear them fully and still stand in my conviction when I know I'm right."]}
  ]},
  {num:"03",tag:"Creative Courage",name:"Grow and Prosper Through Co-Creation",qs:[
    {q:"When I design a learning programme or intervention, I typically…",o:["Build it myself based on the brief and deliver it to the learners.","Consult with a manager or subject matter expert before designing.","Involve learners and stakeholders in the design process, though not as consistently as I would like.","Co-create from the start — with learners, SMEs, operational leaders and sometimes the community itself."]},
    {q:"When something I have designed or delivered has not worked well, I…",o:["Feel responsible and a little defensive about it.","Reflect privately and try to improve it next time.","Debrief with the team and make changes, though I sometimes take it personally.","Treat it as useful data and a shared learning experience. Failure is part of the design process."]},
    {q:"When I think about how I am growing as an L&D or HR professional right now, I would say…",o:["I am focused on doing my job well. My own development feels like something I'll get to later.","I read articles and attend the occasional webinar, but I don't have a structured approach to my own growth.","I am part of at least one community or network and I am actively developing my practice.","My own development is a genuine priority. I am in communities, reading, experimenting and seeking challenge."]},
    {q:"When I think about the skills I most need to develop to stay relevant in the next two years, I would say…",o:["I haven't thought about it in structured terms. I develop as things come up.","I know I need to upskill but I'm not sure where to focus first.","I have identified two or three specific areas — data literacy, facilitation, commercial acumen — and I am working on them.","I have a clear personal development roadmap and I am actively investing in the skills the modern profession demands."]},
    {q:"When I think about using AI tools in my work as an L&D or HR professional, I would say…",o:["I haven't really started. I'm not sure where AI fits in what I do.","I've experimented a little but I don't use AI consistently or with a clear purpose.","I use AI tools regularly to save time and enhance my work, though I'm still learning how to use them well.","AI is embedded in how I work. I use it to accelerate design, analyse data, personalise learning and generate insight — and I understand its limits."]},
    {q:"When I think about the people I work with and the solutions I create, I would say…",o:["I mostly deliver to people — they come to the programme and I facilitate it.","I try to involve people but ownership usually stays with me.","There is a sense of shared ownership in some of my work, and I am building more of it.","The people I work with feel genuine ownership of the learning. We built it together and they carry it forward."]}
  ]},
  {num:"04",tag:"Identity Courage",name:"Know Your Professional Identity",qs:[
    {q:"If someone asked me to describe my professional values in one minute, I would…",o:["Struggle to articulate them clearly. I haven't thought about it in those terms.","Give a general answer about wanting to help people and make a difference.","Be able to name two or three values that feel genuinely mine, though I don't always live by them under pressure.","Give a clear, considered answer that reflects how I actually make decisions every day."]},
    {q:"When the L&D or HR function is undervalued or overlooked in my organisation, I…",o:["Feel frustrated and defeated. It confirms a nagging sense that what I do doesn't really matter.","Accept it as the reality of the profession and try not to take it personally.","Challenge the perception where I can and look for ways to demonstrate value, though it takes its toll.","Feel settled. My sense of professional worth doesn't depend on whether others understand it. I know what I contribute."]},
    {q:"When I am under pressure from a stakeholder to do something I don't believe is right, I…",o:["Usually go along with it. It's easier and safer than pushing back.","Express mild concern but ultimately deliver what is asked.","Push back more often than not, though I sometimes compromise more than I should.","Hold my professional ground with confidence and evidence. I adapt my style without abandoning my values."]},
    {q:"When I think about what makes me distinctive as an L&D or HR professional, I would say…",o:["I'm not sure I am particularly distinctive. I do a solid job but couldn't articulate what sets me apart.","I have some strengths, though I find it hard to talk about them without feeling like I'm showing off.","I know what I'm good at and I'm getting better at owning it and talking about it.","I have a clear sense of my distinctive contribution and I'm not shy about naming it. My identity is my credibility."]},
    {q:"When I think about how AI is changing the L&D and HR profession, my honest reaction is…",o:["Anxiety. I worry about what it means for my role and whether I will be relevant.","Cautious interest — I can see the potential but I'm not sure how to engage with it confidently.","Curious and mostly optimistic — I see AI as something to work with rather than fear, and I'm actively learning.","Energised. I understand that AI will automate what is routine and amplify what is human. I know which side of that line I sit on."]},
    {q:"When I consider how my organisation currently uses AI in people practices — hiring, learning, performance — I would say…",o:["I'm not sure we use AI in these areas, or if we do I'm not involved in those decisions.","We use some AI tools but mostly for efficiency. I haven't thought critically about the implications.","I am aware of how AI is being used and I have some concerns about fairness and transparency that I am beginning to raise.","I actively advocate for ethical AI use in our people practices. I ask hard questions about bias, consent, transparency and human oversight."]}
  ]},
  {num:"05",tag:"Deep Courage",name:"Deep Self-Awareness",qs:[
    {q:"When I am in a challenging professional situation, my awareness of my own body is…",o:["I honestly don't pay much attention to what my body is doing. I just get on with it.","I notice some tension or discomfort but I don't really know what to do with it.","I am becoming more aware of my physical responses and starting to use that awareness to make better choices.","I listen to my body as a source of intelligence. It tells me things my thinking mind misses, and I act on that."]},
    {q:"When I think about the patterns I repeat in my professional life — how I respond to authority, conflict or failure — I would say…",o:["I haven't thought about it in those terms. I just respond how I respond.","I'm aware I have some patterns but I haven't done much to understand or change them.","I'm actively noticing my patterns and beginning to understand where some of them come from.","I have done meaningful work on my own shadow — the unconscious patterns that used to run my practice. I know them and I work with them."]},
    {q:"When I think about my investment in my own inner development — coaching, supervision, reflective practice — I would say…",o:["It's not something I prioritise. I focus on external development — skills, knowledge, qualifications.","I do some reflection but it's mostly informal and I don't give it much dedicated time.","I have a reflective practice and I invest in my own inner development, though not as consistently as I'd like.","My inner development is a non-negotiable. I invest in it regularly and consider it the foundation of everything else I do."]},
    {q:"When I think about the statement 'you cannot take someone somewhere you have not been yourself', I feel…",o:["It's a nice idea but I'm not sure it applies to my work practically.","It resonates but I'm honest enough to admit I sometimes ask more of others than I ask of myself.","I feel this deeply and it motivates me to keep doing my own work, even when it's uncomfortable.","This is the belief that drives my entire practice. My rooms feel exactly as courageous as I am."]},
    {q:"When I am honest about my fears around AI and what it means for my professional future, I would say…",o:["I am genuinely worried. I don't know how to position myself in a world where AI can do so much of what I do.","I have some anxiety about it but I push it away rather than face it directly.","I have sat with the fear and I am beginning to understand what it is telling me — mostly that I need to keep developing.","I have moved through the fear. I know that the most human parts of what I do — judgment, presence, courage, connection — cannot be automated."]},
    {q:"When I think about what it means to use AI ethically in my professional practice, I would say…",o:["I haven't thought about AI ethics in relation to my own work specifically.","I know ethics in AI matters but I wouldn't know how to apply that thinking practically in my role.","I think about transparency, bias and human oversight when I use or recommend AI tools, even if I'm still learning.","Ethical AI use is something I take seriously and advocate for. I ask who benefits, who might be harmed, and whether there is meaningful human oversight in every AI-enabled decision."]}
  ]}
];

const stageInsights={
  "Deep Drift":{
    def:"Deep Drift describes a professional who has settled into a pattern of reactive, order-taking practice. The work gets done — sessions are delivered, content is created, requests are fulfilled — but the practice is disconnected from strategic intent, business impact and professional growth. It is not laziness. It is often the result of years of conditioning in organisations that never asked for more.",
    pros:["Reliable and consistent in delivery","Low conflict — rarely pushes back on requests","Technically competent within established routines","Trusted to fulfil the brief as given"],
    cons:["Invisible at leadership level — not seen as a strategic voice","Little to no measurement of actual impact","High risk of redundancy as AI replaces routine delivery","Professional identity is fragile — defined by output, not contribution","Burnout risk from being permanently in production mode"],
    relevance:"In the current L&D landscape, organisations are under pressure to prove the ROI of learning investment. L&D professionals who remain in Deep Drift are increasingly vulnerable — not because they lack skill, but because they lack visibility and strategic positioning. The profession is at a crossroads: those who stay here will find themselves replaced by automation. Those who move will define what modern L&D becomes."
  },
  "Passive Drift":{
    def:"Passive Drift is the stage of unexpressed potential. The professional here has real capability — they know more than they show, see more than they say, and sense that there is a bigger version of their practice waiting. But the default is still safe. Conversations are managed rather than led. Briefs are accepted rather than challenged. The instinct to step up exists — it just keeps getting deferred.",
    pros:["More self-aware than Deep Drift — can see where change is needed","Genuinely capable and often respected by peers","Willing to develop, even if inconsistently","Good relational awareness — reads the room well"],
    cons:["Consistent gap between knowing and doing","Tends to absorb more than they can process — says yes too readily","Professional voice is underused in stakeholder conversations","Growth is reactive rather than intentional","Prone to imposter syndrome, which reinforces safe behaviour"],
    relevance:"This stage is where a significant proportion of experienced L&D professionals sit — and it is one of the most costly places for both the individual and the organisation. The profession loses enormous value when capable people hold back. For the modern L&D leader, breaking out of Passive Drift is not a skills problem — it is a courage problem. The question is not 'can I do this?' but 'will I choose to?'"
  },
  "Aware Drift":{
    def:"Aware Drift — the Courage Point — is the most charged position on the continuum. This professional understands the model, has done some of the thinking, and can articulate exactly what Drive looks like. They are often the person in the room who sees what needs to change. But seeing it and consistently acting on it are different things. The gap here is not knowledge. It is the habit of hesitation in the moment it matters most.",
    pros:["High self-awareness — genuinely understands their own patterns","Can speak the language of impact and strategy","Trusted by peers and beginning to build stakeholder credibility","Already moving — this is not a fixed state, it is a live decision point"],
    cons:["Can get stuck in analysis — thinking rather than acting","Inconsistency: operates in Drive sometimes, retreats in high-pressure moments","Frustrating for those around them who can see what they are capable of","Risk of intellectualising the journey rather than committing to it","Can use self-awareness as a shield rather than a springboard"],
    relevance:"The Courage Point is where the modern L&D profession is being asked to grow right now. Organisations need L&D professionals who can move from knowing to doing — from designing learning to leading change. The professionals who break through Aware Drift become the ones who shape culture, challenge assumptions and sit at the table where decisions are made. Those who do not break through remain consultants to themselves — full of insight, short on impact."
  },
  "Early Drive":{
    def:"Early Drive is the stage of active, intentional professional practice. The professional here has made a genuine commitment to something beyond delivery — to impact, to influence, to being a force for change rather than a fulfiller of requests. They are visible in the business, they hold their ground with evidence, they challenge briefs and build real relationships with stakeholders. The practice is not perfect — there are still moments of retreat — but the direction is clear and the commitment is real.",
    pros:["Commercially credible — speaks the language of the business","Builds trust through outcomes, not just relationships","Courageous in the room — can challenge, redirect and hold a position","Growing professional identity — clear about what they stand for","Increasingly visible at senior level"],
    cons:["Can overcorrect — drive and directness without enough relational attunement","Sustaining Drive requires ongoing inner work — neglect this and regression is real","May struggle to bring the rest of the team with them","The gap between their practice and those still in Drift can create friction","Not yet fully consistent — high-pressure moments can still produce retreat"],
    relevance:"Early Drive is where the modern L&D profession needs its critical mass to sit. These are the professionals who are redefining what L&D means in their organisations — moving the function from training provider to strategic partner. In a world where AI is automating the delivery layer of learning, the human who can think, challenge, connect and lead is irreplaceable. Early Drive is not a ceiling — it is a launchpad."
  },
  "Full Drive":{
    def:"Full Drive is the stage of mature, integrated professional presence. This professional has done the inner work alongside the outer work. They are commercially credible, relationally courageous, creatively bold and grounded in a clear professional identity. They do not need external validation to know their worth. They are in the rooms where decisions are made, and they speak in those rooms with clarity and conviction. But what truly distinguishes Full Drive is this: the professional here understands that their most important job is to raise the standard of everyone around them.",
    pros:["Strategic voice — genuinely influences organisational direction","Deep credibility built on outcomes, relationships and integrity","Psychologically resilient — does not collapse under pressure or criticism","Clear professional identity — knows exactly what they stand for and why","Acts as a force multiplier — elevates the practice of the people around them"],
    cons:["Risk of isolation — can feel ahead of the culture they are working in","Responsibility to keep doing the inner work, even at this stage","Must guard against arrogance — Full Drive requires ongoing humility","The standard they hold themselves to can make collaboration harder if not managed with care","Requires organisational conditions to be fully expressed — not every culture is ready"],
    relevance:"Full Drive is not a title, a salary band or a number of years of experience. It is a practice — one that has to be chosen and renewed every day. For modern L&D, Full Drive professionals are the ones who are genuinely future-proofing the profession. They are the ones who demonstrate that learning is a strategic function, not a support service. They are the ones who will still be essential when everything routine has been automated. If you are here, your most urgent question is not 'what do I still need to learn?' It is 'who am I helping to get here?'"
  }
};

